This is a known breaking change. Android 15 (which .NET 10 targets by default) fully removes `SOFT_INPUT_ADJUST_RESIZE`. The replacement is the **WindowInsets** API combined with MAUI's built-in `KeyboardAutoManagerScroll`.

## Quick fix — two options:

### Option 1: Let MAUI handle it (simplest)

Wrap your chat layout in a `ScrollView`. MAUI's `KeyboardAutoManagerScroll` (enabled by default) will auto-scroll to keep the focused `Entry`/`Editor` visible:

```xml
<ScrollView>
    <Grid RowDefinitions="*,Auto">
        <CollectionView Grid.Row="0" ItemsSource="{Binding Messages}" />
        <Entry Grid.Row="1" Placeholder="Type a message..." />
    </Grid>
</ScrollView>
```

### Option 2: Handle insets manually (more control)

In your `Platforms/Android/MainActivity.cs`:

```csharp
using Android.Views;
using AndroidX.Core.View;

protected override void OnCreate(Bundle? savedInstanceState)
{
    base.OnCreate(savedInstanceState);

    ViewCompat.SetOnApplyWindowInsetsListener(Window!.DecorView, new InsetsListener());
}

private class InsetsListener : Java.Lang.Object, IOnApplyWindowInsetsListener
{
    public WindowInsetsCompat OnApplyWindowInsets(View v, WindowInsetsCompat insets)
    {
        var imeInsets = insets.GetInsets(WindowInsetsCompat.Type.Ime());
        var navInsets = insets.GetInsets(WindowInsetsCompat.Type.NavigationBars());

        // Bottom padding = keyboard height (or nav bar if keyboard closed)
        int bottom = Math.Max(imeInsets.Bottom, navInsets.Bottom);
        v.SetPadding(0, 0, 0, bottom);

        return insets;
    }
}
```

Also ensure your `AndroidManifest.xml` has:
```xml
<activity android:windowSoftInputMode="adjustResize" ... />
```

Even though the old resize mode is gone, this hint still signals intent to the insets system.

### iOS

On iOS this generally works out of the box. If not, set `KeyboardAutoManagerScroll.Disconnect()` and use a `Margin` bound to keyboard height via platform-specific event listeners.

---

**TL;DR:** The simplest path is Option 1 — put your layout in a `ScrollView` and let `KeyboardAutoManagerScroll` do the work. Use Option 2 if you need pixel-precise control over the bottom padding.
